table.name: MAF Plausibility Check - Low RPM Threshold
if Engine Speed is less than this value, MAF Plausibility Check will be ignored

table.description: The ECU runs through a section of code to check for TPS and/or MAF plausibility to detect sensor errors that aren't due to simple disconnects. The ECU has a rough Alpha N map that knows how RPM, TPS, and MAF should relate to one another. If sensor readings fall outside of this range, it will throw a code for plausibility. For example, at 25% Throttle at 3400RPM, you can have a situation where the turbo has spooled up and is generating a lot of airflow. This would never happen in an NA engine so the ECU sees this extra air read by the MAF sensor and thinks something is wrong. But it only checks for this in a narrow window of RPM between 1504 and 3488 and TPS between 13% and 30% in stock form. We can change these thresholds to fool the ECU into never running this code by changing the RPM thresholds.

table.name: MAF Plausibility Check - High RPM Threshold
if Engine Speed is more than this value, MAF Plausibility Check will be ignored

table.description: The ECU runs through a section of code to check for TPS and/or MAF plausibility to detect sensor errors that aren't due to simple disconnects. The ECU has a rough Alpha N map that knows how RPM, TPS, and MAF should relate to one another. If sensor readings fall outside of this range, it will throw a code for plausibility. For example, at 25% Throttle at 3400RPM, you can have a situation where the turbo has spooled up and is generating a lot of airflow. This would never happen in an NA engine so the ECU sees this extra air read by the MAF sensor and thinks something is wrong. But it only checks for this in a narrow window of RPM between 1504 and 3488 and TPS between 13% and 30% in stock form. We can change these thresholds to fool the ECU into never running this code by changing the RPM thresholds.
